window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>1","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"1","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : FINANCIAL ARITHMETIC","question":"A used car was purchased at \u20a6900,000.00. Its value depreciated by 30% in the first year. In each subsequent year, the depreciation was 22% of its value at the beginning of that year. If the car was brought on 1st March, 2011. Calculate, correct to the nearest hundred naira, the value of the car on 28th February, 2015.   (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Cost price = \u20a6900,000.00 ---------(1)  Depreciation for first year = 30/100 x 900,000   = 270,000  balance = 900000 - 270000  depreciation for second year  = 22/100 x 630000   = 138600  Balance  = 630000 - 138600   = \u20a6 491000  Dereciation for the third year = 22/100 x 491,400  = \u20a6108,000  Balance  = 491,4000 - 108108   = 383,292  Depreciation for 4th year = 22/100 x 383292   = \u20a684324.24  Balance  = 383,292 - 84324.24   = \u20a6298967.96  value of car on 28th feb 205 = \u20a6298,967.76  Correct to the nearest hundred naira","marks":"8","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>2>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"The graph of y = 2px2 - p2x = 14 passes through the point (3, 10). Find the values of p.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given:  y = 2px2 - p2x - 14 ---------- *  and the point   (3, 10)  &nbsp\u2193  &nbsp \u2193  &nbspx  &nbsp y  From the point given, y = 10 when x = 3  substitute for y = 10 and x = 3 in *  10 = 2p(3)2 - p2(3) - 14  24 = 18p - 3p2  3p2 - 18p + 24 = 0  Divide through by 3  p2 - 6p + 8 = 0  (p - 4)(p - 2) = 0  p = 4 or 2","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>2>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : SIMULTANEOUS LINEAR EQUATIONS IN TWO VARIABLES","question":"Two lines, 3y - 2x = 21 and 4y + 5x = 5, intersect at the point Q. Find the coordinates of Q.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given: Two equations of two lines  3y - 2x = 21 ----- (1)  4y + 5x = 5 ------ (2)  To get their point of intersection, we must solve simultaneously.  3y - 2x = 21 X 4 -------- (1)  4y + 5x = 5 X 3 --------- (2)    12y - 8x = 84 -------- (3)  12y + 15x = 15 -------- (4)  Substitute (4) from (3)  -23x = 69  x = -3  Substitute for x = -3 in (1)  3y - 2(-3) = 21  3y + 6 = 21  3y = 15  y = 3  \u2234 Point Q(-3, 5) is their point of intersection.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>3>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : LENGTHS AND PERIMETERS","question":"The diagonals of a rhombus are 10.2cm and 9.3cm long. Calculate, correct to one decimal place, the perimeter of the rhombus.  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The rhombus in the question can be interpreted as thus:    From the diagram above, there are 4 right-angled triangles within the rhombus.  * So pick one of the four to get the length of each side of the rhombus    |BC|2 = (5.1)2 + (4.65)2  |BC|2 = 26.01 + 21.6225  |BC|2 = 47.6325  |BC| = &radic;47.6325&nbsp;  |BC| = 6.9cm to one dp  Perimeter, P = 4 \u00d7 6.9 = 27.6cm","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>3>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : SINE, COSINE AND TANGENT OF AN ANGLE","question":"Given that sin x = 3/5 , 0\u00b0  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Given that sinx = 3/5 --------------*  0\u00b0  x is acute; that is x lies in the first quadrant.  Recall: sin\u03b8=OppHyp    From Pythagora's theorem  52 = 32 + (adj)2  25 = 9 + (adj)2  16 = (adj)2  adj = 4  tanx=34;cosx=45  5cosx-4tanx=5(45)-4(34)  4 - 3 = 1","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>4>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram, QOS is a diameter, \u2220RQS = x\u00b0 and \u2220QST = (3x + 15)\u00b0.    Find the value of x.  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Consider \u0394QRS  (3x + 15)\u00b0 = 90\u00b0 + x {exterior angle of a triangle is equal to the sum of the two opposite interior angles}  3x + 15 = 90 + x  2x = 75  x = 37.5","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>4>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : ANGLES","question":"In the diagram, QOS is a diameter, \u2220RQS = x\u00b0 and \u2220QST = (3x + 15)\u00b0.  Find \u2220RSQ  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"=180\u00b0-(37.5\u00b0+90\u00b0)  =180-127.5\u00b0=52.5\u00b0","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>4>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : NUMBER BASES","question":"If 2N4seven = 15Nnine, find the value of N.  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given that 2N4seven = 15Nnine  2N4seven = 15Nnine  convert both sides to base 10  (2 \u00d7 72) + (N \u00d7 71) + (4 \u00d7 7\u00b0) = (1 \u00d7 92) + (5 \u00d7 91) + (N \u00d7 90)  98 + 7N + 4 = 81 + 45 + N  6N = 24  N = 4","marks":"8","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>5>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"If the mean of m, n, s, p and q is 12, calculate the mean of (m + 4), (n - 3), (s + 6), (p - 2) and (q + 8).  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"mean(x\u0305)=\u2211xn    12=m+n+s+p+q5  m + n + s + p + q = 60 -------------- *  The mean of (m + 4), (n - 3), (s + 6), (p - 2) and ( q + 8)  m + 4 + n - 3 + 5 + 6 + p - 2 + q + 85=m + n + s + p + q + 135=60 + 135=735  \u2192735=14.6","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>5>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"In a community of 500 people, the 75th percentile age is 65 years while the 25th percentile age is 15 years. How many of the people are between 15 and 65 years?  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Total number of people = 500  75th percentile age is 65 ---------- *  25th percentile age is 15 ----------- **    Q3=34\u00d7500=375thposition  \u2234 Q3 = 375th position = 65 years    Q1=14\u00d7500=125thposition  \u2234 Q1 = 125th position = 15 years  There are 250 people between 15 and 65 years   number of people between 15 and 65 years  = 375 - 125 = 250  Hint: 125th to 375th position has 250 entries (people).","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>6>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"In a road worthiness test on 240 cars,60% passed. The number that failed had faults in Clutch, Brakes and Steering as follows: Clutch only - 28; Clutch and Steering - 14; Clutch, Steering and Brakes - 8, Clutch and Brakes - 20, Brakes and Steering only - 6. The number of cars with faults in Steering only is twice the number of cars with faults in Brakes only.    Draw a Venn diagram to illustrate this information.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Total number of cars = 240  60% passed. This means that 40% failed   40100\u00d7240=96peoplefailed  Let C, B and S represent clutch, brake and steering respectively.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>6>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"In a road worthiness test on 240 cars,60% passed. The number that failed had faults in Clutch, Brakes and Steering as follows: Clutch only - 28; Clutch and Steering - 14; Clutch, Steering and Brakes - 8, Clutch and Brakes - 20, Brakes and Steering only - 6. The number of cars with faults in Steering only is twice the number of cars with faults in Brakes only.  How many cars had faulty Brakes?  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"28 + 2x + x + 12 + 6 + 6 + 8 = 96    60 + 3x = 96     3x = 36    x = 12    Faulty brakes = 12 + 12 + 8 + 6 = 38","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>6>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"In a road worthiness test on 240 cars,60% passed. The number that failed had faults in Clutch, Brakes and Steering as follows: Clutch only - 28; Clutch and Steering - 14; Clutch, Steering and Brakes - 8, Clutch and Brakes - 20, Brakes and Steering only - 6. The number of cars with faults in Steering only is twice the number of cars with faults in Brakes only.  How many cars had only one fault?  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Cars with only one fault = 28 + 2x + x    = 28 + 3x = 28 + 3(12)    = 28 + 36 = 64","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>7>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"COORDINATE GEOMETRY OF STRAIGHT LINES : CONCEPT OF THE X-Y PLANE AND COORDINATES OF POINTS ON THE X-Y PLANE","question":"Find the equation of the line passing through the points (2, 5) and (-4, -7).","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Given two points A(2, 5) and B(-4, -7)  First get the slope (m)    Finding the equation of the line means to express it in the form y = mx + c ------- ***  m=y2-y1x2-x1  m=-7-5-4-2=-12-6=2  m = 2  Just pick any of the two points to evaluate c, i.e the y-intercept  (2, 5)  &nbsp\u2193  &nbsp \u2193  &nbspx  &nbsp y  5 = 2(2) + c  &nbsp\u2193  &nbsp \u2193  y = m(x) + c  5 = 4 + c  c = 1  \u2234 The equation of the line is y = 2x + 1","marks":"8","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>7>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : BEARINGS","question":"Three ships P, Q and R are at sea. The bearing of O from P is 030\u00b0 and the bearing of P from R is 300\u00b0. If |PQ| = 5km and |PR| = 8km.    Illustrate the information in a diagram.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>7>b>ii>I","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"I","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : BEARINGS","question":"Three ships P, Q and R are at sea. The bearing of O from P is 030\u00b0 and the bearing of P from R is 300\u00b0. If |PQ| = 5km and |PR| = 8km.  Calculate, correct to three significant figures, the distance between Q and R.  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"\u0394PQR is a right-angle triangle  y2 = 82 + 52  y2 = 64 + 25  y2 = 89  y = &radic;89&nbsp; = 9.43km = |QR|    Apply SOH CAH TOA, to find  tan\u03b8=85  tan\u03b8 = 1.6  \u03b8 = tan-1(1.60)  \u03b8 = 57.99\u00b0  N.B: 30\u00b0 + x = 57.99\u00b0  x = 27.99\u00b0    The bearing of R from Q = 90\u00b0 + 62.01\u00b0 = 152\u00b0 to 3.s.f","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>7>b>ii>II","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"II","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : BEARINGS","question":"Three ships P, Q and R are at sea. The bearing of O from P is 030\u00b0 and the bearing of P from R is 300\u00b0. If |PQ| = 5km and |PR| = 8km.  Calculate, correct to three significant figures, the bearing of R from Q.  (Leaving the answer in two decimal place)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The distance between Q and R, |QR| = 9.43km to 3.s.f.","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>8>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : PROFIT AND LOSS","question":"Lamin bought a book for \u20a6300.00 and sold it to Bola at a profit of x%. Bola then sold the same book to James at a profit of x%. If James paid \u20a6 ( 6x + 3/4 ) more for the book than what Lamin paid, find the value of x.  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Cost Price = \u20a6300.00 (Lamin's cost price)  % Profit = x% (When Lamin sold it to Bola)  % Profit = x% (When Bola sold the same book to James)  * It should be noted that James paid \u20a6(6x + 3/4) more for the book than what Lamin paid.    From Lamin's Side  x100=y - 300300(%profit=SP-CPCP\u00d7100)  y = selling price to Bola or Bola's cost price  x=y - 3003  3x + 300 = y -----*    From Bola's side  x100=z - yy  N.B: z = selling price to James  x100=z - (3x + 300)(3x + 300)  (3x + 300)x = 100[z - (3x + 300)]  3x2 + 300x = 100(z - 3x - 300)  3x2 + 300x = 100z - 300x - 30000 -------------      We are told in the question that James paid \u20a6(6x + 3/4) more for the book than what lamin did.  z=300+(6x+34)-------*  From   3x2+600x+30000100=z-----------**  Equate (3) and (4)  300+(6x+34)=3x2+600x+30000100  100(300+6x+34)=3x2+600x+30,000  30,000 + 600x + 75 = 3x2 + 600x + 30,000  3x2 = 75  x2 = 25  x = &radic;25&nbsp; = 5","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>8>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : LINEAR INEQUALITIES","question":"Find the range of values of x which satisfies the inequality 3x - 2","images":[],"marking_scheme":"3x - 2  3x - 2  2x  x  10 + x  8  4x > 8  x > 2  x > 2 or x  \u2234 The range of values of x is 2","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>9>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : TRIANGLES AND POLYGONS","question":"In the diagram, |PT| = 4cm, |TS| = 6cm, |PQ| = 6cm and \u2220SPR = 30\u00b0. Calculate, correct to the nearest whole number;    |SR|  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"There are two similar triangle in the diagram above, \u0394PSR and \u0394PTQ    PTPS=PQPR=TQSR  \u0394PTQ  We can apply cosine rule to evaluate |TQ|, i.e x.  x2 = 42 + 62 - 2(4)(6)cos30\u00b0  x2=16+36-2(24)(&radic;3&nbsp;2)  x2 = 52 - 24&radic;3&nbsp;  x2 = 10.431  x = &radic;10.431&nbsp;  x = 3.23cm  |TQ| = 3.23    From (1)  410=3.23SR  0.4(SR) = 3.23  SR=3.230.4  |SR| = 8.0cm to the nearest whole number.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>9>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : AREAS","question":"In the diagram, |PT| = 4cm, |TS| = 6cm, |PQ| = 6cm and \u2220SPR = 30\u00b0. Calculate, correct to the nearest whole number;  Area of TQRS","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Area of TQRS  If we look at the diagram carefully,  Area of \u0394PSR = Area of \u0394PTQ + Area of TQRS ------- (2)    * To calculate the area of \u0394PSR  12\u00d7PS\u00d7PR\u00d7sin30\u00b0  We know that |PS| = 10cm, but |PR| is unknown.  From (1)  410=66+QR  0.4=66+QR  2.4 + 0.4|QR| = 6  3.6 = 0.4|QR|  |QR| = 9.0cm  |PR| = |PQ| + |QR|  |PR| = 6cm + 9cm = 15cm  \u2234Areaof\u0394PSR=12\u00d710\u00d715\u00d7sin30\u00b0   = 75 \u00d7 1/2 = 37.5cm2  * To Calculate area of \u0394PTQ  12\u00d7PT\u00d7PQ\u00d7sin30\u00b0  =12\u00d74\u00d76\u00d712=6.0cm2  From (2)  37.5cm2 = 6.0cm2 + Area of TQRS  Area of TQRS = 31.5cm2.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>10>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : TRIANGLES AND POLYGONS","question":"In \u0394PQS, |PQ| = 12cm, |PS| = 5cm, \u2220SPQ = \u2220PrQ = 90\u00b0. Find, correct to three significant figures, |PR|.  (Leaving the answer in two decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Consider \u0394PSR    We can use Pythagora's theorem to find |SQ|  |SQ|2 = |PS|2 + |PQ|2  |SQ|2 = 52 + 122  |SQ|2 = 169  |SQ| = &radic;169&nbsp; = 13cm.  Let us find the value of \u03b2  sin\u03b2=513  \u03b2=sin-1(513)  \u03b2 = sin-1(0.385)  \u03b2 = 226\u00b0    sin22.6=PR12  12 \u00d7 sin22.6\u00b0 = PR  PR=12\u00d7513=6013=4.62to3sf","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>10>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : ANGLES OF ELEVATION AND DEPRESSION","question":"The lengths of two ladders, L and M are 10m and 12m respectively. They are placed against a wall such that each ladder makes the same angle with the horizontal ground. If the foot of L is 8m from the foot of the wall.   Draw a diagram to illustrate this information.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>10>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : ANGLES OF ELEVATION AND DEPRESSION","question":"The lengths of two ladders, L and M are 10m and 12m respectively. They are placed against a wall such that each ladder makes the same angle with the horizontal ground. If the foot of L is 8m from the foot of the wall.  Calculate the height at which M touches the wall.  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"N.B: \u0394LXF and \u0394MXT are similar \u0394s  From \u0394LXF  sin\u03b8=810  sin\u03b8 = 0.8  \u03b8 = sin-1(0.8)  \u03b8 = 53.13\u00b0 ------ *    cos53.13\u00b0=h12  12 \u00d7 cos53.13 = h  h = 0.6 \u00d7 12 = 7.2cm  M touches the wall at a height of 7.2cm","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>11>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : FORMULATION AND EVALUATION OF ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES","question":"Copy and complete the table of values for y = 2x2 + x - 10 for -5 \u2264 x \u2264 4.  x-5-4-3-2-101234y5-9-100","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given: y = 2x2 + x - 10 ----------- *  Range of values -5 \u2264 x \u2264 4 ----------- **  x-5-4-3-2-101234y5-9-100  Use the equation given to complete the table by plugging in different values of x into y = 2x2 + x - 10  - When x = -5  y = 2(-5)2 + (-5) - 10  y = 2(25) - 5 - 10  y = 50 - 15 = 35    - When x = -4  y = (-4)2 + (-4) - 10  y = 32 - 4 - 10  y = 32 - 14 = 18    - When x = -3  y = 2(-3)2 + (-3) - 10  y = 2(9) - 3 - 10  y - 18 - 13 = 5    - When x = -2  y = 2(-2)2 + (-2) - 10  y = 2(4) - 2 - 10   = 8 - 12 = -4    - When x = -1  y = 2(-1)2 + (-1) - 10  y = 2(1) - 1 - 10  y = 2 - 11 = -9    - When x = 0  y = 2(0)2 + (0) - 10  y = 0 + 0 - 10  y = -10    - When x = 1  y = 2(1)2 + (1) - 10  y = 2 + 1 - 10  y = -7    - When x = 2  y = 2(2)2 + (2) - 10  y = 8 + 2 - 10  y = 10 - 10 = 0    - When x = 3  y = 2(3)2 + (3) - 10  y = 2(9) + 3 - 10  y = 18 + 3 - 10  y = 21 - 10 = 11    - When x = 4  y = 2(4)2 + (4) - 10  y = 2(16) + 4 - 10  y = 32 + 4 - 10  y = 36 - 10  y = 26  Now we can complete the table.  x-5-4-3-2-101234y35185-4-9-10-701126","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>11>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Using scales of 2cm to 1 unit on the x-axis and 2cm to 5 units on the y-axis, draw the graph of y = 2x2 + x - 10 for -5 \u2264 x \u2264 4.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>11>c>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Use the graph to find the solution of 2x2 + x = 10","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The solution of 2x2 + x = 10, from the graph is x = -2.5 or x = 2.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>11>c>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Use the graph to find the solution of 2x2 + x - 10 = 2x","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The question demands that we find the points of intersection of y = 2x and y = 2x2 + x - 10  y = 2x2 + x - 10  \u2234 2x = 2x2 + x - 10  2x2 - x - 10 = 0  2x + 4x - 5x - 10 = 0   2x(x + 2) - 5(x + 2) = 0  x = 2.5 or x = -2  You have actually deduced the points of intersection, to draw line correctly, note that the line will pass through the origin, since c = 0;  y = 2x  y = mx + c","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>12>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : ALGEBRAIC FRACTIONS","question":"Ifx=23,y=5-2andz=-413,findscalarspandqsuchthatpx+qy=z.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given:  Ifx=23,y=5-2andz=-413  px + qy = z ---------- *  P23+q5-2=-413  2P3P+5q-2q=-413  2P + 5q = -4 ------------ (1) \u00d7 3  3P - 2q = 13 ------------ (2) \u00d7 2  6P + 15q = -12  6P - 4q = 26  19q = -38  q = -2  Substitute for q = -2 in (1)  2P + 5(-2) = -4  2P - 10 = -4  2P = 6  P = 3  P = 3 and q = -2","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>12>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Using a scale of 2cm to 2 units on both axes, draw on a graph paper two perpendicular axes 0x and 0y for -5 \u2264 x \u2264 5, -5 \u2264 y \u2264 5 respectively.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":".","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>12>b>ii>I","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"I","group":"","topic":"COORDINATE GEOMETRY OF STRAIGHT LINES : CONCEPT OF THE X-Y PLANE AND COORDINATES OF POINTS ON THE X-Y PLANE","question":"Draw, on the graph paper, indicating clearly the vertices and their coordinates, the quadrilateral WXYZ with W(2, 3), X(4, -1), Y(-3, -4) and Z(-3, 2)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>12>b>ii>II","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"II","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND TRANSFORMATION : TRANSFORMATION IN THE CARTESIAN PLANE","question":"Draw, on the graph paper, indicating clearly the vertices and their coordinates, the image W1 X1 Y1 Z1 of the quadrilateral WXYZ under an anticlockwise rotation of 90\u00b0 about the origin where W \u2192 W1, X \u2192 X1, Y \u2192 Y1 and Z \u2192 Z1.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>13>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"Marks102030405060708090Frequency11x5y1431  The frequency table shows the marks distribution of a class of 30 students in an examination. The mean mark of the distribution is 52.    Find the values of x and y.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given: The table below  Marks102030405060708090Frequency11x5y1431  Total frequency = 30  Mean mark = 52  Recall:Mean(x\u0305)=\u2211fx\u2211f---------------*  52=10(1) + 20(1) + 30(x) + 40(5) + 50(y) + 60(1) + 70(4) + 80(3) + 90(1)30  52=10 + 20 + 30x + 200 + 50y + 60 + 280 + 240 + 9030  1560 = 900 + 30x + 50y  30x + 50y = 660  3x + 5y = 66 --------------(1)  30 = 1 + 1 + x + 5 + y + 1 + 4 + 3 + 1  30 = 16 + x + y  x + y = 14 ---------------- (2)  combine (1) and (2)  3x + 5y = 66 -------------- (1) \u00d7 1  x + y = 14 ----------------- (2) \u00d7 3  3x + 5y = 66  3x + 3y = 42  2y = 24  y = 12  substitute for y = 12 in (2)  x + 12 = 14  x = 2  (x, y) = (2, 12)","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2018>13>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"Marks102030405060708090Frequency11x5y1431  The frequency table shows the marks distribution of a class of 30 students in an examination. The mean mark of the distribution is 52.  Construct a group frequency distribution table starting with a lower class limit of 1 and a class interval of 10.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"GROUP FREQUENCY DISTRIBUTION TABLE  Class IntervalFrequency1 - 10  11 - 20  21 - 30  31 - 40  41 - 50  51 - 60  61 - 70  71 - 80  81 - 901  1  2  5  12  1  4  3  1","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"}];